ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': "Title: \nPaper Abstract: Sentence Alignment with Parallel Documents Facilitates Biomedical Machine Translation. Objective: Today's neural machine translation (NMT) can achieve near human-level translation quality and greatly facilitates international communications, but the lack of parallel corpora poses a key problem to the development of translation systems for highly specialized domains, such as biomedicine. This work presents an unsupervised algorithm for deriving parallel corpora from document-level translations by using sentence alignment and explores how training materials affect the performance of biomedical NMT systems. Materials and Methods: Document-level translations are mixed to train bilingual word embeddings (BWEs) for the evaluation of cross-lingual word similarity, and sentence distance is defined by combining semantic and positional similarities of the sentences. The alignment of sentences is formulated as an extended earth mover's distance problem. A Chinese-English biomedical parallel corpus is derived with the proposed algorithm using bilingual articles from UpToDate and translations of PubMed abstracts, which is then used for the training and evaluation of NMT. Results: On two manually aligned translation datasets, the proposed algorithm achieved accurate sentence alignment in the 1-to-1 cases and outperformed competing algorithms in the many-to-many cases. The NMT model fine-tuned on biomedical data significantly improved the in-domain translation quality (zh-en: +17.72 BLEU; en-zh: +17.02 BLEU). Both the size of the training data and the combination of different corpora can significantly affect the model's performance. Conclusion: The proposed algorithm relaxes the assumption for sentence alignment and effectively generates accurate translation pairs that facilitate training high quality biomedical NMT models.\nCandidate Topics: machine translation, natural language processing, translation, sentence, word, earth mover s distance, bleu, key, similarity, similarity, similarity, speech recognition, example based machine translation, semeval, semantic similarity, rule based machine translation, machine learning, automatic summarization, lexical similarity, semantic change, transfer based machine translation, tweaking, machine translation software usability, relation, evaluation of machine translation, cosine similarity, similarity measure, baseline, unified medical language system, paraphrase, similitude, natural language, motion, benchmark, translation memory, gerund, semantic equivalence, speech translation, sleep, edit distance, signal, set, word embedding, paragraph, language translation, morpheme, scratch, computer assisted translation, phrase, word error rate, variation, margin, similarity learning, verb, language model, space, question answering, microwave, quake, relevance, 5g, joint, jaro winkler distance, information retrieval, state, event, open research, textual entailment, generative grammar, perspective, computational linguistics, soar, rotation, drill down, sync, translation unit, representation, statement, embedding, synchronization, thesaurus, interpretability, lemmatisation, pattern recognition, knowledge transfer, transformer, semantics, rework, anime, semantic translation, dynamic