tion cues, and the potential bias towards visual appearance in existing video segmentation models.\nCandidate Topics: optical flow, segmentation, computer vision, image segmentation, artificial intelligence, pattern recognition, visualization, motion, feature extraction, structure from motion, object detection, texture, object, salient, machine learning, deep learning, visual appearance, camouflage, field, contextual image classification, segmentation based object categorization, scale space segmentation, motion estimation, traffic flow, transformer, image, image texture, inference, categorization, robustness, motion analysis, motion field, artificial neural network, pairwise comparison, image quality, similarity, trifocal tensor, texture, frame, light field, traffic analysis, embedding, parallax, binary classification, contrast, video tracking, fuzzy logic, ground truth, pattern recognition, image processing, conditional random field, image fusion, salience, kadir brady saliency detector, active appearance model, traffic classification, rendering, discriminative model, semantics, match moving, markov random field, entropy, traffic generation model, animation, f1 score, flownet, data mining, triangulation, baseline, orientation, feature, similarity, local binary patterns, motion detection, machine vision, stability, biometrics, translation, eye tracking, structural similarity, key, texture mapping, shape analysis, solid modeling, tracking, traffic shaping, pixel, motion capture, contrast, cognitive neuroscience of visual object recognition, traffic engineering, identification, grayscale, unsupervised learning, latent variable, machine translation, topological map, matching, image resolution, ransac'}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all attempts. Saving errors: [{'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceeded! Current cost: 5.423352675000006, Max budget: 5.0', 'type': 'budget_exceeded', 'param': None, 'code': '400'}}, {'error': {'message': 'Budget has be