ation of: output performance; efficacy; and real-world use of AI systems, and synthesising the key themes according to the stages of evaluation: pre-clinical (theoretical phase); exploratory phase; definitive phase; and post-market surveillance phase (monitoring). The result is a framework to guide AI system developers, policymakers, and regulators through a sufficient evaluation of an AI system designed for use in healthcare.\nCandidate Topics: knowledge management, data science, key, artificial intelligence, domain, analytics, decision support system, event, ontology, factor, knowledge engineering, subject matter expert, complement, competitive intelligence, open research, relevance, component, data mining, predictive analytics, set, focus, field, software engineering, variety, simulation, innovation management, domain knowledge, statement, control, workflow, cloud computing, interpretation, open data, variation, applications of artificial intelligence, clinical decision support system, learning analytics, body of knowledge, business intelligence, data analysis, knowledge representation and reasoning, software, factoid, information management, value, decision field theory, intelligent decision support system, tacit knowledge, principal, relation, operator, measure, requirements engineering, sci fi, critical success factor, mathematical knowledge management, sensemaking, knowledge base, case based reasoning, human intelligence, knowledge extraction, risk factor, library science, evidential reasoning approach, perspective, knowledge based systems, capability maturity model, process, hang, machine learning, knowledge acquisition, variable, cover, dissemination, intelligence analysis, problem domain, risk assessment, nexus, presentation, descriptive knowledge, traceability, service, requirement, intelligence cycle, capability maturity model integration, predictive modelling, computational intelligence, leverage, knowledge market, subject, procedural knowledge, expert 