ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Title: \nPaper Abstract: Dataset Summarization by K Principal Concepts. We propose the new task of K principal concept identification for dataset summarizarion. The objective is to find a set of K concepts that best explain the variation within the dataset. Concepts are high-level human interpretable terms such as "tiger", "kayaking" or "happy". The K concepts are selected from a (potentially long) input list of candidates, which we denote the concept-bank. The concept-bank may be taken from a generic dictionary or constructed by task-specific prior knowledge. An image-language embedding method (e.g. CLIP) is used to map the images and the concept-bank into a shared feature space. To select the K concepts that best explain the data, we formulate our problem as a K-uncapacitated facility location problem. An efficient optimization technique is used to scale the local search algorithm to very large concept-banks. The output of our method is a set of K principal concepts that summarize the dataset. Our approach provides a more explicit summary in comparison to selecting K representative images, which are often ambiguous. As a further application of our method, the K principal concepts can be used to classify the dataset into K groups. Extensive experiments demonstrate the efficacy of our approach.\nCandidate Topics: set, machine learning, data mining, principal, identification, embedding, local search, local optimum, cluster analysis, artificial intelligence, pattern recognition, feature vector, automatic summarization, support vector machine, variation, robustness, local search, feature, feature extraction, text mining, feature, principal component analysis, selection, feature learning, unsupervised learning, algorithm, natural language processing, information retrieval, key, theoretical computer science, linear discriminant analysis, search algorithm, landmark, initialization, feature selection, algorithm design, small set, concept drift, optimization problem, image, computer vision, ranking, extension, multi document summarization, contextual image classification, variety, word embedding, supervised learning, artificial neural network, large set, single linkage clustering, algorithmic learning theory, pattern recognition, entropy, relevance, noise, projection, field, mutation, signal, representation, statement, salient, vector space model, test set, isolation, linear programming, global optimization, distance matrix, presentation, language model, sentence, centroid, document clustering, probabilistic logic, data set, multivariate statistics, univariate, ranking, dimensionality reduction, gradient descent, combinatorial optimization, statistical classification, language identification, search problem, baseline, stability, mutual information, pixel, pairwise comparison, visualization, concept mining, euclidean distance, principal variation search, random projection, discriminative model, determining the number of clusters in a data set, word, k means clustering, decomposition'}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all attempts. Saving errors: [{'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceeded! Current cost: 5.423352675000006, Max budget: 5.0', 'type': 'budget_exceeded', 'param': None, 'code': '400'}}, {'error': {'me