ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': "Title: \nPaper Abstract: Frozen in Time: A Joint Video and Image Encoder for End-to-End Retrieval. Our objective in this work is video-text retrieval - in particular a joint embedding that enables efficient text-to-video retrieval. The challenges in this area include the design of the visual architecture and the nature of the training data, in that the available large scale video-text training datasets, such as HowTo100M, are noisy and hence competitive performance is achieved only at scale through large amounts of compute. We address both these challenges in this paper. We propose an end-to-end trainable model that is designed to take advantage of both large-scale image and video captioning datasets. Our model is an adaptation and extension of the recent ViT and Timesformer architectures, and consists of attention in both space and time. The model is flexible and can be trained on both image and video text datasets, either independently or in conjunction. It is trained with a curriculum learning schedule that begins by treating images as 'frozen' snapshots of video, and then gradually learns to attend to increasing temporal context when trained on video datasets. We also provide a new video-text pretraining dataset WebVid-2M, comprised of over two million videos with weak captions scraped from the internet. Despite training on datasets that are an order of magnitude smaller, we show that this approach yields state-of-the-art results on standard downstream video-retrieval benchmarks including MSR-VTT, MSVD, DiDeMo and LSMDC.\nCandidate Topics: joint, artificial intelligence, image retrieval, embedding, the internet, image, closed captioning, visualization, encoder, encoding, computer vision, multimedia, information retrieval, task, feature extraction, benchmark, representation, code, speech recognition, schedule, transfer of learning, artificial neural network, motion, pattern recognition, deep learning, machine learning, network architecture, translation, question answering, sentence, feature learning, scheduling, end to end principle, adaptation, reinforcement learning, pooling, extension, image processing, image translation, pyramid, server, automatic image annotation, signal, discriminative model, presentation, immersion, image warping, hallucinating, natural language processing, image segmentation, pyramid, key, matching, robot, process, data compression, ranking, service, query expansion, automatic summarization, language model, thesaurus, data modeling, frame, pipeline, iterative reconstruction, video tracking, theoretical computer science, sequence learning, visual reasoning, data mining, web page, graph, feature, motion capture, margin, histogram, representation, scheme, audio signal, robustness, annotation, event, pattern recognition, variety, ranking, segmentation, inpainting, pose, real time computing, synchronization, initialization, session, transfer, state, animation, unsupervised learning, interpolation, edge, visual appearance"}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all attempts. Saving errors: [{'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceeded! Current cost: 5.423352675000006, Max budget: 5.0', 'type': 'budget_exceeded', 'param': None, 'code': '400'}}, {'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceed