ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Title: \nPaper Abstract: SST-GNN: Simplified Spatio-temporal Traffic forecasting model using Graph Neural Network. To capture spatial relationships and temporal dynamics in traffic data, spatio-temporal models for traffic forecasting have drawn significant attention in recent years. Most of the recent works employed graph neural networks(GNN) with multiple layers to capture the spatial dependency. However, road junctions with different hop-distance can carry distinct traffic information which should be exploited separately but existing multi-layer GNNs are incompetent to discriminate between their impact. Again, to capture the temporal interrelationship, recurrent neural networks are common in state-of-the-art approaches that often fail to capture long-range dependencies. Furthermore, traffic data shows repeated patterns in a daily or weekly period which should be addressed explicitly. To address these limitations, we have designed a Simplified Spatio-temporal Traffic forecasting GNN(SST-GNN) that effectively encodes the spatial dependency by separately aggregating different neighborhood representations rather than with multiple layers and capture the temporal dependency with a simple yet effective weighted spatio-temporal aggregation mechanism. We capture the periodic traffic patterns by using a novel position encoding scheme with historical and current data in two different models. With extensive experimental analysis, we have shown that our model has significantly outperformed the state-of-the-art models on three real-world traffic datasets from the Performance Measurement System (PeMS).\nCandidate Topics: data mining, dependency, recurrent neural network, scheme, machine learning, artificial intelligence, algorithm, artificial neural network, time series, real time computing, encoding, theoretical computer science, data modeling, time delay neural network, pattern recognition, simple, routing, graph, data stream mining, deep learning, representation, graphical model, leverage, visualization, convolutional neural network, convolution, hidden markov model, feature extraction, computation, aggregate, association rule learning, robustness, embedding, algorithm design, dependency theory, feature, relationship extraction, dependency graph, synthetic data, network model, data visualization, kernel, feature learning, data dependency, sensor fusion, computational complexity theory, markov chain, sequence learning, layer, complex network, radar, kernel, simulation, data set, node, traffic generation model, temporal database, functional dependency, state, regression analysis, evolving networks, distributed computing, tree, data stream, waveform, data structure, inference, redundancy, dependency relation, long term prediction, complex systems, word, chain rule, simplicity, higher order statistics, temporal difference learning, computer engineering, relation, exploit, sequence labeling, class, decorrelation, dependence analysis, pattern matching, dependency grammar, forward chaining, schedule, expression, motion, signal, spatial correlation, class, reliability, kernel, multipath routing, dependency network, extension, unsupervised learning, data science, pattern recognition'}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all atte