ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Title: \nPaper Abstract: Misinformation detection in Luganda-English code-mixed social media text. The increasing occurrence, forms, and negative effects of misinformation on social media platforms has necessitated more misinformation detection tools. Currently, work is being done addressing COVID-19 misinformation however, there are no misinformation detection tools for any of the 40 distinct indigenous Ugandan languages. This paper addresses this gap by presenting basic language resources and a misinformation detection data set based on code-mixed Luganda-English messages sourced from the Facebook and Twitter social media platforms. Several machine learning methods are applied on the misinformation detection data set to develop classification models for detecting whether a code-mixed Luganda-English message contains misinformation or not. A 10-fold cross validation evaluation of the classification methods in an experimental misinformation detection task shows that a Discriminative Multinomial Naive Bayes (DMNB) method achieves the highest accuracy and F-measure of 78.19% and 77.90% respectively. Also, Support Vector Machine and Bagging ensemble classification models achieve comparable results. These results are promising since the machine learning models are based on n-gram features from only the misinformation detection dataset.\nCandidate Topics: cross validation, social media, natural language processing, machine learning, support vector machine, naive bayes classifier, language model, natural language, discriminative model, word2vec, misinformation, test set, classifier, semi supervised learning, sentiment analysis, information retrieval, data set, classifier, world wide web, cross language information retrieval, data validation, synthetic data, machine translation, crowdsourcing, code, test data, multi label classification, set, overfitting, noisy text, supervised learning, data mining, malware, data modeling, sentence, bag of words model, word, versa, ensemble learning, ground truth, e commerce, collocation, word embedding, source code, microblogging, data set, baseline, multiclass classification, cross entropy, word error rate, disinformation, computational linguistics, embedding, semeval, text mining, data science, knowledge base, crowdsourced testing, modeling language, desk, bootstrapping, linear classifier, structured support vector machine, open data, data model, variety, boosting, noisy text analytics, information extraction, online machine learning, wordnet, field, multinet, identification, key, mobile device, question answering, manually coded language, ensemble forecasting, use case, automatic label placement, data classification, adaboost, deep learning, contextual image classification, binary classification, cross reference, leverage, document classification, false positives and false negatives, linear model, noise, section, concatenated sms, the internet, cover, cross site scripting, ransomware, autoencoder, artificial intelligence'}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all attempts. Saving errors: [{'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceeded! Current cost: 5.423352675000006, Max budget: 5.0', 'type': 'budget_exceeded', 'param': None, 'code': '400'}}, {'error': {'message': 'Budget has be