ess without sacrificing clean accuracy. Our analysis for this work is done using six types of white-box attacks and two types of black-box attacks. Our study encompasses multiple Vision Transformers, Big Transfer Models and CNN architectures trained on CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100 and ImageNet.\nCandidate Topics: adversarial system, transformer, artificial intelligence, robustness, contextual image classification, convolutional neural network, deep learning, machine learning, artificial neural network, adversary, computer security, cryptography, network security, adversarial machine learning, critical infrastructure, feature extraction, computer vision, encryption, computer engineering, data mining, theoretical computer science, network architecture, image, pattern recognition, image processing, authentication, classifier, arbiter, applications of artificial intelligence, boosting, statistical classification, algorithm, inference, visual reasoning, visualization, leverage, security analysis, visual cryptography, critical infrastructure protection, cognitive neuroscience of visual object recognition, image segmentation, encoder, information security, categorization, neural cryptography, machine vision, malware, image retrieval, resilience, contrast, feature learning, formal verification, key, mnist database, supervised learning, pattern recognition, computational intelligence, transform coding, provable security, data modeling, cloud computing, transfer of learning, layer, normalization, detector, modular design, oracle, random forest, computation, data security, algorithm design, recurrent neural network, rectifier, artificial intelligence system, facial recognition system, systems design, security engineering, observer, entropy, adversarial information retrieval, airport security, image resolution, adversarial process, modular neural network, eavesdropping, hidden markov model, amplifier, vulnerability, classifier, adversary model, encoding, telecommunications, server, infr