ERROR:root:Request {'model': 'protected.gpt-4.1-mini', 'messages': [{'role': 'system', 'content': "\n    You will receive a paper abstract along with a set of candidate topics for the paper. \n    Your first task is to select the topics that best align with the core theme of the paper.\n    Exclude topics that are too broad or less relevant. \n    Only use the topic names in the candidate set. \n    Your second task is to generate a complete list of key phrases extracted from the paper.\n    Do some rationalization before outputting the list of relevant topics and key phrases.\n    Output format: '<top> topic 1, topic 2, ... </top><kp>key phrase 1, key phrase 2, ... </kp>'.\n    "}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Title: \nPaper Abstract: Thinking Fast and Slow: Efficient Text-to-Visual Retrieval with Transformers. Our objective is language-based search of large-scale image and video datasets. For this task, the approach that consists of independently mapping text and vision to a joint embedding space, a.k.a. dual encoders, is attractive as retrieval scales and is efficient for billions of images using approximate nearest neighbour search. An alternative approach of using vision-text transformers with cross-attention gives considerable improvements in accuracy over the joint embeddings, but is often inapplicable in practice for large-scale retrieval given the cost of the cross-attention mechanisms required for each sample at test time. This work combines the best of both worlds. We make the following three contributions. First, we equip transformer-based models with a new fine-grained cross-attention architecture, providing significant improvements in retrieval accuracy whilst preserving scalability. Second, we introduce a generic approach for combining a Fast dual encoder model with our Slow but accurate transformer-based model via distillation and re-ranking. Finally, we validate our approach on the Flickr30K image dataset where we show an increase in inference speed by several orders of magnitude while having results competitive to the state of the art. We also extend our method to the video domain, improving the state of the art on the VATEX dataset.\nCandidate Topics: transformer, embedding, inference, encoder, artificial intelligence, machine learning, search engine indexing, scalability, deep learning, image retrieval, computer engineering, feature extraction, image, theoretical computer science, artificial neural network, visualization, encoding, data mining, contextual image classification, quantization, computer vision, pattern recognition, representation, visual reasoning, domain, word embedding, translation, discriminative model, task, feature learning, image translation, inference engine, categorization, algorithm, quantization, semantics, testbed, language model, transform coding, key, state, leverage, benchmark, decoding methods, image resolution, contrast, mnist database, transfer of learning, convolutional neural network, knowledge engineering, natural language processing, feature, orientation, image processing, reinforcement learning, analytics, extension, visual word, real time computing, information retrieval, natural language, embedded system, doors, field, property, recurrent neural network, formal verification, nearest neighbor search, memory architecture, k nearest neighbors algorithm, data modeling, ranking, question answering, curse of dimensionality, search engine, knowledge extraction, convolution, probabilistic logic, continuous embedding, robotics, applications of artificial intelligence, order embedding, pyramid, measure, algorithm design, computation, feature, metrical task system, spatial intelligence, robustness, kernel, block, view synthesis, implementation, computational intelligence, compression, auxiliary memory, jpeg, projection, approximate inference'}], 'stream': False, 'seed': 347} failed after all attempts. Saving errors: [{'error': {'message': 'Budget has been exceeded! Current cost: 5.