rom our approach are: (i) high quality and comparable to a known knowledge graph-based embeddings and can be used to improve them further, (ii) better than a contextual language model-based entity embeddings, and (iii) easy to compute and versatile in domain-specific applications where a knowledge graph is not readily available\nCandidate Topics: natural language processing, natural language, representation, natural language understanding, language model, information retrieval, knowledge base, representation, world wide web, knowledge engineering, graph, semantic similarity, information model, question answering, knowledge representation and reasoning, semantics, external data representation, theoretical computer science, semantic network, semantic web, machine learning, similarity, embedding, modeling language, ontology, text graph, information extraction, knowledge transfer, human computer interaction, knowledge extraction, social network, knowledge based systems, data modeling, semantic data model, semantic equivalence, data model, domain knowledge, interpretability, query language, text mining, traceability, social semantic web, data science, commonsense knowledge, explicit semantic analysis, universal networking language, open knowledge base connectivity, domain, key, semantic computing, graph database, information exchange, knowledge modeling, knowledge sharing, statistical relational learning, descriptive knowledge, body of knowledge, data mining, feature learning, word embedding, knowledge integration, data structure, unified modeling language, rdf, knowledge management, the internet, set, web modeling, semantic search, network model, procedural knowledge, feature, interoperability, leverage, tree structure, n gram, encyclopedia, categorization, information framework, graphical model, inference, search engine, semantic analysis, feature engineering, relationship extraction, word, statistical model, common data representation, scalability, structured predicti