iffuse and specular albedos, a more sophisticated illumination model and a plausible representation of self-shadows. This enables to take a big leap forward in reconstruction quality of shape, appearance and lighting even in scenes with difficult illumination. With consistent face attributes reconstruction, our method leads to practical applications such as relighting and self-shadows removal. Compared to state-of-the-art methods, our results show improved accuracy and validity of the approach.\nCandidate Topics: iterative reconstruction, rendering, monocular, ray tracing, robustness, artificial intelligence, image formation, computer vision, deep learning, stereopsis, ray casting, global illumination, solid modeling, encoder, image based lighting, artificial neural network, inference, 3d reconstruction, supervised learning, reinforcement learning, shading, photometric stereo, generative grammar, initialization, luminance, interpolation, path tracing, spherical harmonic lighting, feature learning, pose, generative model, convolutional neural network, pattern recognition, machine learning, image segmentation, structured light, computer graphics images, tracing, unsupervised learning, rgb color model, feature extraction, pixel, pascal, algorithm, segmentation, visualization, image based modeling and rendering, computational photography, image, distributed ray tracing, face, intrinsics, image resolution, inpainting, epipolar geometry, beam tracing, computer graphics, robot, voxel, image restoration, depth map, identifiability, reconstruction algorithm, compositing, transformation geometry, robotics, frame, prior probability, 3d rendering, cone tracing, representation, unbiased rendering, skeletonization, benchmark, consistency, computational geometry, computation, skeleton, network formation, stereo camera, object detection, robot learning, image processing, adversarial system, per pixel lighting, inheritance, principle of compositionality, routing, encoding, sensory c